choices.text:
to ride a motorcycle taxi called a pousse-pousse. The pousse-pousse (or pichidina) is called a pop-pop taxi in Seychelles. But either way, they are little cart contraptions pulled along by a tiny moto that seems to hop dangerously at times as it is packed with clients.

Anyway, where were we?

Oh yes, the Christmas stockings! In the center of the little wooden stocking is 2PCS of delicious dried kesala, the famous Sambirano Valley cocoa nibs called kandia. Two kandia and one chacotty will keep you going for most of the next trip to the pousse-pousse to grocery store.

Note that in many of the photos the packaging looks quite primitive, because actually, it’s the packing! Once on the truck or boat, this packaging is expertly packaged in very sophisticated ways to ensure the chocolate is safely delivered.

I can’t even say how impressed I was with this packing and in particular the injection of nitrogen into all the packets! Nitrogen keeps the chocolate stable. This is truly beyond what I would ever know to do… (Well, probably could know to do if I had 25 years to dedicate to learning about this stuff)…

The plastic wrap over top, the heat-sealed packaging, the injection with nitrogen gas AND, that all incorporates compostable bags, vegetable plastic wrap covering the top and all the packaging paper is all made totally out of sustainable and compostable materials
